center based in Berkeley.

00:05:07.450 --> 00:05:10.460
And we help increase access
for people with disabilities.

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:16.200
One of the reasons I'm
really excited to be here

00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:19.275
is that Google has an
extraordinary mission

00:05:19.275 --> 00:05:22.050
to organize the
information of the world,

00:05:22.050 --> 00:05:26.230
and make it
accessible, and useful.

00:05:26.230 --> 00:05:29.950
In honor of the 25th
anniversary of the Americans

00:05:29.950 --> 00:05:32.950
with Disabilities
Act, I want to talk

00:05:32.950 --> 00:05:36.560
about what we can do
to make information

00:05:36.560 --> 00:05:38.705
more accessible for
people with disabilities.

00:05:41.390 --> 00:05:43.563
So first, I want to talk
about communication.

00:05:46.220 --> 00:05:47.500
I'm deaf-blind.

00:05:47.500 --> 00:05:50.620
So if you have a question,
and raise your hand,

00:05:50.620 --> 00:05:53.245
it's going to be up
there for a long time.

00:05:53.245 --> 00:05:55.420
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:55.420 --> 00:05:58.800
And if you shout it out, I'm
not going to be able to hear it.

00:05:58.800 --> 00:06:02.130
So for communication, I use a
keyboard in Braille display.

00:06:04.312 --> 00:06:07.260
I'll hold up the
Braille display.

00:06:07.260 --> 00:06:10.650
On the bottom are
mechanical pins

00:06:10.650 --> 00:06:14.050
that pop up to form
Braille letters.

00:06:14.050 --> 00:06:16.810
And when someone
types on the keyboard,

00:06:16.810 --> 00:06:20.770
it shows up in digital Braille.

00:06:20.770 --> 00:06:23.700
Technology helps
a lot of people.

00:06:23.700 --> 00:06:27.230
And as programmers and
technology developers,

00:06:27.230 --> 00:06:30.040
you really change the lives
of people with disabilities.

00:06:32.570 --> 00:06:37.590
The technology I use
was developed by people.

00:06:37.590 --> 00:06:40.170
And they've changed my
life, and they continue

00:06:40.170 --> 00:06:42.890
to change the lives of others.

00:06:42.890 --> 00:06:45.400
And all of you
here have the power

00:06:45.400 --> 00:06:49.220
to help people, and really
change the lives of people.

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:56.520
One in four Americans
have a disability

00:06:56.520 --> 00:06:59.140
at some point in their life.

00:06:59.140 --> 00:07:01.780
That's a huge segment
of the population.

00:07:01.780 --> 00:07:03.820
It includes the elderly.

00:07:03.820 --> 00:07:08.400
It includes people who
are born with disabilities

00:07:08.400 --> 00:07:14.450
and people who have experiences,
or temporary disabilities.

00:07:14.450 --> 00:07:17.490
So thinking about
designing technologies

00:07:17.490 --> 00:07:19.570
that will reach
these communities,

00:07:19.570 --> 00:07:23.490
and empower them to gain
access to information,

00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:24.800
it's really, really meaningful.

00:07:27.890 --> 00:07:32.120
There are a variety of assistive
technologies people use.

00:07:32.120 --> 00:07:36.460
Screen readers, are one example.

00:07:36.460 --> 00:07:39.470
Screen readers are
applications that

00:07:39.470 --> 00:07:44.760
convert graphical information
into synthesize speech,

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:47.640
or digital Braille, like the
Braille display I was holding.

00:07:50.630 --> 00:07:54.730
These serve as bridges that
allow blind individuals

00:07:54.730 --> 00:07:59.140
to access information
on screens.

00:07:59.140 --> 00:08:04.260
So when developers put in
hooks for their products,

00:08:04.260 --> 00:08:07.800
and services to connect
with screen readers,

00:08:07.800 --> 00:08:10.660
blind individuals are
able to gain access

00:08:10.660 --> 00:08:15.890
to online services,
and other products.

00:08:15.890 --> 00:08:20.410
Another feature is
closed captioning.

00:08:20.410 --> 00:08:24.260
Closed captioning are
subtitles on the bottom

00:08:24.260 --> 00:08:29.610
of videos that allow deaf
individuals to access

00:08:29.610 --> 00:08:31.290
the audio content on videos.

00:08:34.659 --> 00:08:37.400
Closed captioning is a feature
that helps the deaf and hard

00:08:37.400 --> 00:08:38.630
of hearing community.

00:08:38.630 --> 00:08:41.429
But it also helps to
other communities.

00:08:41.429 --> 00:08:47.760
Often places will have videos
with the audio turned off,

00:08:47.760 --> 00:08:51.280
and closed captions turned on.

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:55.300
So little things like that
end up helping everyone.

00:08:55.300 --> 00:08:58.340
Keyboard shortcuts
are helpful for people

00:08:58.340 --> 00:09:02.680
with mobility disabilities
that affect the use of hands.

00:09:02.680 --> 00:09:05.650
But they're also helpful for
people who just plain don't

00:09:05.650 --> 00:09:07.600
like using mice.

00:09:07.600 --> 00:09:10.080
Sometimes it's faster to
use keyboard shortcuts.

00:09:12.470 --> 00:09:16.600
So these are all features
that people have developed,

00:09:16.600 --> 00:09:20.650
that engineers, programmers,
technology developers

00:09:20.650 --> 00:09:24.650
have imagined creating, and
then went through and created,

00:09:24.650 --> 00:09:28.110
and have changed how people
engage with information,

00:09:28.110 --> 00:09:29.250
and engage with each other.

00:09:32.470 --> 00:09:38.870
Technology has revolutionized
all aspects of our lives

00:09:38.870 --> 00:09:44.890
from entertainment, to
reading, to shopping.

00:09:44.890 --> 00:09:50.800
Online shopping has really
impacted the lives of people

00:09:50.800 --> 00:09:55.100
with disabilities in the
area of physical access.

00:09:55.100 --> 00:09:57.740
A lot of stores,
physical stores,

00:09:57.740 --> 00:10:00.120
have physical
barriers, like stairs,

00:10:00.120 --> 00:10:04.220
that make it hard for someone in
a wheelchair to get in and out,

00:10:04.220 --> 00:10:07.850
if there are no
accessible entrances.

00:10:07.850 --> 00:10:12.290
And online shopping gives
people the opportunity

00:10:12.290 --> 00:10:14.450
to bypass those
physical obstacles.

00:10:17.240 --> 00:10:25.380
Chat programs, blogging programs
have allowed many communities

00:10:25.380 --> 00:10:29.430
to start engaging, and having
conversations, that might not

00:10:29.430 --> 00:10:32.690
have otherwise occurred.

00:10:32.690 --> 00:10:36.290
Individuals on the
autism spectrum,

00:10:36.290 --> 00:10:39.930
individuals who are
deaf or hard of hearing,

00:10:39.930 --> 00:10:45.710
are now having conversations,
and connecting, and engaging.

00:10:45.710 --> 00:10:48.250
And programmers, and
technology developers

00:10:48.250 --> 00:10:54.230
who have built these programs,
like Google Hangouts,

00:10:54.230 --> 00:10:57.300
have allowed individuals
in those communities

00:10:57.300 --> 00:11:00.040
to connect, and
share their voices.

00:11:02.920 --> 00:11:08.290
So as developers of technology,
you have a very powerful tool.

00:11:08.290 --> 00:11:13.250
And in some ways, it's
opened many doors.

00:11:13.250 --> 00:11:20.130
The vast majority of websites,
and apps, are not accessible.

00:11:20.130 --> 00:11:22.160
But you can change that.

00:11:22.160 --> 00:11:26.195
It's an incredible gift and
tool that you have to change.

00:11:29.770 --> 00:11:33.560
The process is about
designing products

00:11:33.560 --> 00:11:37.540
from the start with hooks
for assistive technology,

00:11:37.540 --> 00:11:43.430
like screen readers, allowing
for captioning, allowing

00:11:43.430 --> 00:11:45.810
for keyboard shortcuts.

00:11:45.810 --> 00:11:48.900
And when you design it from
the start with those features

00:11:48.900 --> 00:11:52.690
in mind, you're able
to ensure that it's

00:11:52.690 --> 00:11:54.990
going to be accessible.

00:11:54.990 --> 00:11:59.480
Helping people with disabilities
participate in the process

00:11:59.480 --> 00:12:06.080
by allowing for testing at
every stage of development,

00:12:06.080 --> 00:12:08.820
those are ways to
ensure that products

00:12:08.820 --> 00:12:10.950
can help all Americans.

00:12:14.010 --> 00:12:18.720
The challenge is continually
coming up with ways

00:12:18.720 --> 00:12:22.430
to ensure that
people can connect.

00:12:22.430 --> 00:12:24.450
Sometimes it's
really challenging,

00:12:24.450 --> 00:12:26.810
and you get stuck
in a comfort zone

00:12:26.810 --> 00:12:30.090
where you're doing
something just one way.

00:12:30.090 --> 00:12:35.451
And it becomes difficult to
imagine new, exciting ways

00:12:35.451 --> 00:12:36.450
for sharing information.

00:12:39.280 --> 00:12:41.380
But this is Google.

00:12:41.380 --> 00:12:44.630
This is Google, with an
extraordinary mission

00:12:44.630 --> 00:12:47.200
to organize the
information of the world,

00:12:47.200 --> 00:12:49.380
and make it
accessible, and useful.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:55.660
I'm not a technology developer.

00:12:55.660 --> 00:12:57.760
I'm not a programmer.

00:12:57.760 --> 00:13:01.050
So I don't know all
the technical details

00:13:01.050 --> 00:13:04.160
of the challenges involved.

00:13:04.160 --> 00:13:08.390
But I do know how hard it
is to continue imagining

00:13:08.390 --> 00:13:09.500
new ways of doing things.

00:13:12.640 --> 00:13:15.815
One way I connect with
people is through dance.

00:13:18.330 --> 00:13:21.450
I've been dancing
for about 10 years.

00:13:21.450 --> 00:13:24.340
And because I can't
hear the music,

00:13:24.340 --> 00:13:27.570
and I can't see what my
dance friends are doing,

00:13:27.570 --> 00:13:30.450
I had to come up
with alternative ways

00:13:30.450 --> 00:13:34.290
of experiencing rhythm,
and knowing the dance

00:13:34.290 --> 00:13:38.780
moves by using my hands.

00:13:38.780 --> 00:13:41.560
In over 10 years,
I've come up with lots

00:13:41.560 --> 00:13:44.350
of different techniques
for accessing

00:13:44.350 --> 00:13:48.150
the rhythm, and the movements.

00:13:48.150 --> 00:13:52.050
But I realized that there was
still one very important thing

00:13:52.050 --> 00:13:55.550
that I just wasn't picking up.

00:13:55.550 --> 00:14:01.400
About two weeks ago I was
dancing, and during the dance,

00:14:01.400 --> 00:14:05.100
the guy I was dancing with
raised his hand to his face

00:14:05.100 --> 00:14:09.140
and signed, smiling.

00:14:09.140 --> 00:14:11.750
I felt so surprised.

00:14:11.750 --> 00:14:14.550
He's telling me he's smile?

00:14:14.550 --> 00:14:18.170
What a beautiful thing to
communicate smiling while

00:14:18.170 --> 00:14:19.540
dancing.

00:14:19.540 --> 00:14:22.980
It never occurred to me.

00:14:22.980 --> 00:14:31.070
Smiles are visually available
information to most people.

00:14:31.070 --> 00:14:34.970
And now I know that
when I'm dancing,

00:14:34.970 --> 00:14:39.300
I can tell people-- By the
way, if you're smiling,

00:14:39.300 --> 00:14:45.600
and you want to tell me,
you could sign smiling.

00:14:45.600 --> 00:14:51.570
So sometimes it's challenging to
think of new ways to do things.

00:14:51.570 --> 00:14:54.330
But it's a fun challenge,
and very rewarding.

00:15:00.460 --> 00:15:05.510
And when you come up with new
ways of presenting information,

00:15:05.510 --> 00:15:08.720
you reach more
people, and it moves

00:15:08.720 --> 00:15:12.140
Google closer to its
goal, its mission,

00:15:12.140 --> 00:15:14.490
of gathering the
information, and making

00:15:14.490 --> 00:15:18.460
it accessible, and useful.

00:15:18.460 --> 00:15:21.740
Features that help the
disability community

00:15:21.740 --> 00:15:26.060
often end up helping
the greater community.

00:15:26.060 --> 00:15:28.419
Closed captioning
helps people who

00:15:28.419 --> 00:15:29.585
are deaf or hard of hearing.

00:15:32.310 --> 00:15:37.570
The text associated
with those videos

00:15:37.570 --> 00:15:41.500
serves as a way to
allow for greater,

00:15:41.500 --> 00:15:46.750
more powerful keyword
searches, allowing people

00:15:46.750 --> 00:15:51.250
to access exactly the video,
and information, they want.

00:15:51.250 --> 00:15:54.750
So a feature like closed
captioning, and other assistive

00:15:54.750 --> 00:15:57.950
technologies, end up helping
the greater community.

00:16:03.050 --> 00:16:07.110
I'm really, really
excited to see how we all

00:16:07.110 --> 00:16:09.870
move towards the mission
of making information

00:16:09.870 --> 00:16:13.060
more accessible for everyone.

00:16:13.060 --> 00:16:17.040
About 25 years ago, Congress
passed the Americans

00:16:17.040 --> 00:16:19.800
with Disabilities Act.

00:16:19.800 --> 00:16:24.420
And it represents our country's
belief that everyone's equal,

00:16:24.420 --> 00:16:27.120
and everyone deserves
opportunities in America.

00:16:29.730 --> 00:16:33.060
There are challenges
associated with technology,

00:16:33.060 --> 00:16:38.730
but also, almost
unlimited potential.

00:16:38.730 --> 00:16:43.040
The World Wide Web Consortium
has created resources

00:16:43.040 --> 00:16:45.990
to help with technical
specifics on how

00:16:45.990 --> 00:16:49.230
to make services accessible.

00:16:49.230 --> 00:16:53.300
The Web Content
Accessibility Guidelines 2.0

00:16:53.300 --> 00:16:55.130
is an excellent resource.

00:16:55.130 --> 00:17:00.250
For mobile applications,
the BBC mobile

00:17:00.250 --> 00:17:03.780
accessibility guidelines.

00:17:03.780 --> 00:17:08.060
But also here at Google,
there are many resources,

00:17:08.060 --> 00:17:12.619
and many people, who have this
information of what it takes

00:17:12.619 --> 00:17:15.655
to make services, and
products accessible to people

00:17:15.655 --> 00:17:16.404
with disabilities.

00:17:20.540 --> 00:17:26.700
The disability community wants
to access all the information

00:17:26.700 --> 00:17:33.090
online, wants too access all
the websites and services.

00:17:33.090 --> 00:17:37.170
We want to be part
of the digital world.

00:17:37.170 --> 00:17:42.170
We want to be able to use the
apps in the Google Play Store.

00:17:42.170 --> 00:17:46.230
And later we want
to drive your cars.

00:17:46.230 --> 00:17:47.715
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:49.200 --> 00:17:51.790
I'm excited to see
where Google goes,

00:17:51.790 --> 00:17:54.650
and where we all
go, towards the goal

00:17:54.650 --> 00:17:57.450
of making information
accessible for everyone.

