00:18:13.426 --> 00:18:14.800
AUDIENCE: So my
question to Haben

00:18:14.800 --> 00:18:18.100
is, you just came back
from the White House.

00:18:18.100 --> 00:18:22.370
I saw Obama in the photograph,
as well as Joe Biden.

00:18:22.370 --> 00:18:23.680
What was the experience like?

00:18:23.680 --> 00:18:25.645
What did you discuss?

00:18:25.645 --> 00:18:27.020
HABEN GIRMA: It
was unbelievable.

00:18:30.480 --> 00:18:33.030
I went to the White
House in celebration

00:18:33.030 --> 00:18:36.060
of the 25th anniversary
of the Americans

00:18:36.060 --> 00:18:37.940
with Disabilities Act.

00:18:37.940 --> 00:18:40.300
And there were disability
rights advocates

00:18:40.300 --> 00:18:46.170
from all over the country
gathered to celebrate.

00:18:46.170 --> 00:18:52.080
And I gave introductory
remarks before Obama's speech.

00:18:52.080 --> 00:18:54.980
And I met President
Barack Obama,

00:18:54.980 --> 00:18:57.540
and spoke at them briefly.

00:18:57.540 --> 00:19:01.600
And he used the
technology we have here.

00:19:01.600 --> 00:19:04.110
He typed on the
keyboard, and I read

00:19:04.110 --> 00:19:06.520
what he was typing on
the Braille display.

00:19:06.520 --> 00:19:09.660
And I voiced my responses.

00:19:09.660 --> 00:19:13.940
And we talked about
typing, and communication.

00:19:13.940 --> 00:19:16.440
And then I thanked
him for his work

00:19:16.440 --> 00:19:21.410
in helping to increase access
for people with disabilities.

00:19:21.410 --> 00:19:24.020
What are some of
the big commitments

00:19:24.020 --> 00:19:29.260
the US administration has made
for people with disabilities?

00:19:29.260 --> 00:19:34.080
One major thing, the White
House was celebrating on Monday,

00:19:34.080 --> 00:19:38.144
is increased hiring
people with disabilities.

00:19:38.144 --> 00:19:40.060
They're more and more
people with disabilities

00:19:40.060 --> 00:19:44.980
in all areas of government from
working at the White House,

00:19:44.980 --> 00:19:49.070
to working in different
federal agencies.

00:19:49.070 --> 00:19:57.310
In 2010 President Obama and
the Department of Justice

00:19:57.310 --> 00:20:01.460
announced rule
making that they plan

00:20:01.460 --> 00:20:08.400
to release that would set
regulations for website access.

00:20:08.400 --> 00:20:13.410
And those are just
two of the things.

00:20:13.410 --> 00:20:16.550
But there's a lot
that the US has

00:20:16.550 --> 00:20:20.120
been doing to increase access
for people with disabilities,

00:20:20.120 --> 00:20:26.660
both in the physical world, and
in the online, digital world.

00:20:26.660 --> 00:20:28.200
AUDIENCE: Eunice
is asking, do you

00:20:28.200 --> 00:20:30.790
know how the situation
is in other countries?

00:20:30.790 --> 00:20:36.090
How do, for example, non-Latin
people use Braille display?

00:20:36.090 --> 00:20:38.230
HABEN GIRMA: So do I
know about the situation

00:20:38.230 --> 00:20:42.410
in other countries, and
how they use, for example,

00:20:42.410 --> 00:20:44.890
Braille displays?

00:20:44.890 --> 00:20:47.880
There are many different
types of Braille displays,

00:20:47.880 --> 00:20:49.670
and they have the
ability to present

00:20:49.670 --> 00:20:51.235
Braille in other languages.

00:20:54.610 --> 00:20:58.860
So Braille is supported in many
different languages, including

00:20:58.860 --> 00:21:03.170
Spanish, German, and French.

00:21:03.170 --> 00:21:05.320
And when I've
traveled in Europe,

00:21:05.320 --> 00:21:08.620
I've encountered Braille
in other languages.

00:21:08.620 --> 00:21:12.420
Like in Spain, a lot
of things at stores,

00:21:12.420 --> 00:21:17.732
like shampoo bottles, will
have Braille labels in Spanish.

00:21:17.732 --> 00:21:19.660
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:21.470 --> 00:21:26.090
So there are different
things in other countries.

00:21:26.090 --> 00:21:30.770
And every country approaches
access slightly differently.

00:21:30.770 --> 00:21:35.310
In China, for example,
on the sidewalks

00:21:35.310 --> 00:21:39.030
they have raised to
paths, tactile paths

00:21:39.030 --> 00:21:42.200
in the middle of the sidewalk,
so that a blind person

00:21:42.200 --> 00:21:45.070
can feel with
their feet the path

00:21:45.070 --> 00:21:48.020
in the middle of the sidewalk.

00:21:48.020 --> 00:21:55.850
And I believe both China,
and Japan, and Hong Kong,

00:21:55.850 --> 00:22:01.040
have made an effort to have
audio signals at intersections.

00:22:01.040 --> 00:22:04.920
I've also heard Hong Kong
has Braille labels at street

00:22:04.920 --> 00:22:05.900
corners.

00:22:05.900 --> 00:22:07.570
So when you get to
a street corner,

00:22:07.570 --> 00:22:11.590
you can read what
intersection that is.

00:22:11.590 --> 00:22:13.330
Here in the United
States, we have

00:22:13.330 --> 00:22:18.800
a little bit of that in a
few places, but not as much.

00:22:18.800 --> 00:22:21.490
I've also been to Ethiopia.

00:22:21.490 --> 00:22:26.140
And I know that the
University of Addis Ababa

00:22:26.140 --> 00:22:31.580
has a program that supports
students with disabilities.

00:22:31.580 --> 00:22:34.740
And they're working on
getting more technology.

00:22:34.740 --> 00:22:38.400
But there's a huge need
for funding for technology

00:22:38.400 --> 00:22:44.510
like Braille displays, Braille
printers, Braille books.

00:22:44.510 --> 00:22:48.620
So every country has their
own challenges, but also

00:22:48.620 --> 00:22:51.865
their own unique solutions.

00:22:51.865 --> 00:22:53.240
AUDIENCE: The
question is, thanks

00:22:53.240 --> 00:22:54.770
