00:25:05.880 --> 00:25:09.360
so many potentials,
for the deaf community,

00:25:09.360 --> 00:25:11.980
but also for the
hearing community,

00:25:11.980 --> 00:25:15.700
to allow for greater
interactivity, greater searches

00:25:15.700 --> 00:25:19.080
for video, and information.

00:25:19.080 --> 00:25:24.140
So improving audio captioning
for YouTube videos.

00:25:24.140 --> 00:25:27.891
It would be great if people
could prioritize that.

00:25:27.891 --> 00:25:29.640
AUDIENCE: The question
is, I was wondering

00:25:29.640 --> 00:25:32.000
if you could tell us a little
more about your experience

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:34.340
transitioning from
Harvard after being

00:25:34.340 --> 00:25:36.780
in school for many, many years.

00:25:36.780 --> 00:25:41.050
HABEN GIRMA: I graduated from
Harvard Law School in 2013,

00:25:41.050 --> 00:25:45.060
and then immediately started as
a Skadden fellowship attorney

00:25:45.060 --> 00:25:48.850
at Disability Rights Advocates.

00:25:48.850 --> 00:25:55.180
And the transition
was actually not hard,

00:25:55.180 --> 00:25:59.960
because during law school, I
participated in internships.

00:25:59.960 --> 00:26:02.450
And those internships
gave me an idea

00:26:02.450 --> 00:26:07.300
of what to expect
in the work world.

00:26:07.300 --> 00:26:10.340
And because Disability
Rights Advocates

00:26:10.340 --> 00:26:14.400
is all about supporting
people with disabilities,

00:26:14.400 --> 00:26:18.180
it was-- it is a very
supportive environment

00:26:18.180 --> 00:26:21.380
in getting the accommodations
I need for work.

00:26:21.380 --> 00:26:24.630
So we worked out having a
communication assistant who

00:26:24.630 --> 00:26:29.410
would transcribe phone
calls, transcribes meetings,

00:26:29.410 --> 00:26:34.160
and if there were presentations,
or if I go to court,

00:26:34.160 --> 00:26:37.290
and there's hearings,
to get someone

00:26:37.290 --> 00:26:41.165
to type that information, so I
can have captions in Braille.

00:26:43.970 --> 00:26:48.950
So the transition was
helped by the fact

00:26:48.950 --> 00:26:51.570
that I had internship
opportunities

00:26:51.570 --> 00:26:53.950
while I was in law school.

00:26:53.950 --> 00:26:56.710
I'm also from San
Francisco Bay area.

00:26:56.710 --> 00:26:58.740
I grew up in Oakland.

00:26:58.740 --> 00:27:01.760
And my family's still here,
and I had friends here.

00:27:01.760 --> 00:27:06.250
So moving back
here after school,

00:27:06.250 --> 00:27:08.980
I already had a support network.

00:27:08.980 --> 00:27:13.400
So that helped a whole lot.

00:27:13.400 --> 00:27:16.080
AUDIENCE: The first question
out of two questions she has is,

00:27:16.080 --> 00:27:17.840
what do you have
to say to people

00:27:17.840 --> 00:27:20.940
who do not have disabilities,
and who make excuses

00:27:20.940 --> 00:27:23.350
for not following their dreams?

00:27:23.350 --> 00:27:29.700
And her next question
is, do you also Amharic?

00:27:29.700 --> 00:27:34.440
I watched your videos, and
I learned that your parents

00:27:34.440 --> 00:27:39.065
are from Ethiopia, and Eritrea.

00:27:42.240 --> 00:27:45.310
HABEN GIRMA: My family is
from Eritrea, and Ethiopia.

00:27:45.310 --> 00:27:49.560
My mom grew up in Eritrea, and
my dad grew up in Ethiopia.

00:27:49.560 --> 00:27:55.490
And they both speak Amharic,
Tigrinya, and English.

00:27:55.490 --> 00:27:59.130
So growing up, they
taught me English

00:27:59.130 --> 00:28:02.290
so I could succeed in
education, and work.

00:28:02.290 --> 00:28:05.590
They taught me Tigrinya so
that we could talk in public,

00:28:05.590 --> 00:28:07.272
and no one would understand us.

00:28:07.272 --> 00:28:10.050
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:10.050 --> 00:28:12.462
But they saved Amharic
for themselves,

00:28:12.462 --> 00:28:14.670
so they could have secrets,
and I wouldn't understand

00:28:14.670 --> 00:28:15.586
what they were saying.

00:28:18.090 --> 00:28:23.560
So I don't know Amharic, just
a word or two here and there.

00:28:23.560 --> 00:28:33.740
And I think being Eritrean
has helped a lot in my need

00:28:33.740 --> 00:28:36.170
to pursue dreams.

00:28:36.170 --> 00:28:39.890
Eritreans worked hard
fighting for 30 years

00:28:39.890 --> 00:28:42.960
to gain independence
from Ethiopia.

00:28:42.960 --> 00:28:47.920
And I grew up hearing
those stories.

00:28:47.920 --> 00:28:51.590
It doesn't directly have
to do with disabilities,

00:28:51.590 --> 00:28:54.780
but it taught me that
perseverance is important.

00:28:54.780 --> 00:28:59.800
And it's important to keep
trying, even for 30 years.

00:28:59.800 --> 00:29:03.410
So growing up, I didn't
exactly know all the answers

00:29:03.410 --> 00:29:07.040
to how to do things, as
someone who's deaf-blind.

00:29:07.040 --> 00:29:10.840
Often, I was the first
one trying something.

00:29:10.840 --> 00:29:18.480
Harvard University had Helen
Keller almost 100 years ago.

00:29:18.480 --> 00:29:22.245
And back then the technology
we have doesn't exist.

00:29:24.920 --> 00:29:29.720
She's an incredible role model
for pursuing your dreams,

00:29:29.720 --> 00:29:34.910
and doing things even if you
don't have the technology.

00:29:34.910 --> 00:29:39.740
So I knew that one way or
another, I could do it.

00:29:39.740 --> 00:29:43.320
She did it without computers,
without digital Braille.

00:29:43.320 --> 00:29:45.850
So I could absolutely do it.

00:29:45.850 --> 00:29:47.500
I didn't know exactly how.

00:29:47.500 --> 00:29:49.530
She hadn't gone to law school.

00:29:49.530 --> 00:29:51.790
And she hadn't utilized
the technologies

00:29:51.790 --> 00:29:53.720
that are available.

00:29:53.720 --> 00:29:56.845
But I knew I had to try
and make it work somehow.

00:29:59.670 --> 00:30:03.030
And your first
question, Susanna,

00:30:03.030 --> 00:30:07.420
what do I tell people who don't
have disabilities, and yet,

00:30:07.420 --> 00:30:09.770
have excuses for
not doing something?

00:30:12.780 --> 00:30:15.250
You live only once.

00:30:15.250 --> 00:30:18.280
Your dreams are your dreams.

00:30:18.280 --> 00:30:22.460
And if they mean something
to you, keep trying.

00:30:22.460 --> 00:30:24.780
Keep trying to make them happen.

00:30:24.780 --> 00:30:26.860
If it takes 30
years, it's better

00:30:26.860 --> 00:30:31.790
you tried and win after 30
years, then not trying at all.

00:30:31.790 --> 00:30:34.650
If you don't know how you're
going to do something,

00:30:34.650 --> 00:30:36.840
because you're unique,
and your experiences are

00:30:36.840 --> 00:30:41.130
different from others,
take a deep breath,

00:30:41.130 --> 00:30:44.030
and start brainstorming.

00:30:44.030 --> 00:30:46.610
Use the skills that you do have.

00:30:46.610 --> 00:30:51.830
Network with other people, and
get advice from other people.

00:30:51.830 --> 00:30:53.880
Everyone has dreams.

00:30:53.880 --> 00:30:56.605
And it's up to us
to make them happen.

00:30:58.371 --> 00:30:59.997
[LAUGHTER]

00:30:59.997 --> 00:31:01.830
FEMALE SPEAKER: [? Umrit ?]
is letting Haben

00:31:01.830 --> 00:31:04.170
know that her jokes were a hit.

00:31:04.170 --> 00:31:06.660
The whole room was laughing.

00:31:06.660 --> 00:31:08.455
And [? Gopi ?] was
signing with smiles.

00:31:11.850 --> 00:31:14.245
HABEN GIRMA: Thank you.

00:31:14.245 --> 00:31:15.620
FEMALE SPEAKER:
Daniel is typing,

00:31:15.620 --> 00:31:18.310
I'm deaf, functionally
hearing impaired.

00:31:18.310 --> 00:31:21.040
I'm very impressed
with your enunciation.

00:31:21.040 --> 00:31:23.970
My question is, how does
the situation in the US

00:31:23.970 --> 00:31:27.780
compare to other G10
countries in terms

00:31:27.780 --> 00:31:33.070
of disability legislation,
and also good faith

00:31:33.070 --> 00:31:36.970
adherence to the law?

00:31:41.417 --> 00:31:43.500
HABEN GIRMA: That's something
that a lot of people

00:31:43.500 --> 00:31:45.340
have been researching.

00:31:45.340 --> 00:31:51.150
Every community has different
attitudes towards disabilities.

00:31:51.150 --> 00:31:55.290
Some communities celebrate
difference a lot more.

00:31:55.290 --> 00:31:59.820
In China, where the emphasis
is on being the same,

00:31:59.820 --> 00:32:02.570
it's a lot harder
to be different.

00:32:02.570 --> 00:32:06.940
And it's a lot harder
to get accommodations,

00:32:06.940 --> 00:32:12.350
such as interpreters,
captioning, digital Braille.

00:32:12.350 --> 00:32:15.964
But in other cultures, the
individual's uniqueness

00:32:15.964 --> 00:32:16.755
is more celebrated.

00:32:19.480 --> 00:32:24.010
So you asked specifically
about laws and legislation.

00:32:26.600 --> 00:32:31.770
I haven't studied the disability
laws of other countries.

00:32:31.770 --> 00:32:35.230
So I can't offer an
answer to that right now,

00:32:35.230 --> 00:32:37.785
but I'd be happy
to look that up.

00:32:37.785 --> 00:32:39.160
FEMALE SPEAKER:
Kenneth's saying,

00:32:39.160 --> 00:32:41.240
I'm also impressed
with your speech.

00:32:41.240 --> 00:32:43.550
It's usually very
hard for a deaf person

00:32:43.550 --> 00:32:46.410
to learn to speak so well
without audio feedback.

00:32:46.410 --> 00:32:48.605
Can you describe your
own educational process?

00:32:51.180 --> 00:32:53.770
HABEN GIRMA: I will
talk about my education.

00:32:53.770 --> 00:32:55.800
But I also want to
talk about my speech,

00:32:55.800 --> 00:32:57.640
since people seem
to be interested.

00:32:57.640 --> 00:32:58.690
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:59.650 --> 00:33:04.080
So, I identify as deaf-blind.

00:33:04.080 --> 00:33:07.730
And the deaf-blind community
is very, very diverse.

00:33:07.730 --> 00:33:12.850
And that includes everyone
with no vision, and no hearing,

00:33:12.850 --> 00:33:15.420
to a little vision,
and a little hearing.

00:33:15.420 --> 00:33:17.480
And I have a little
bit of hearing

00:33:17.480 --> 00:33:19.790
and a little bit of vision.

00:33:19.790 --> 00:33:23.200
And my low frequency
is terrible.

00:33:23.200 --> 00:33:26.460
I have a really hard time
hearing low frequency sounds.

00:33:26.460 --> 00:33:29.100
Or I just don't
hear them at all.

00:33:29.100 --> 00:33:32.970
High frequency I
can kind of hear.

00:33:32.970 --> 00:33:37.080
And my voice is high frequency.

00:33:37.080 --> 00:33:40.950
And I think I may have
somewhat trained myself

00:33:40.950 --> 00:33:44.140
to speak at a higher
voice to make it easier

00:33:44.140 --> 00:33:46.250
for me to hear myself.

00:33:46.250 --> 00:33:52.270
So that's part of the reason
that I speak the way I speak.

00:33:52.270 --> 00:33:55.010
My education, I grew
up in the Bay Area,

00:33:55.010 --> 00:33:57.720
and I attended
mainstream schools.

00:33:57.720 --> 00:34:01.300
And the school
had a program that

00:34:01.300 --> 00:34:05.180
made sure students who were
blind or students who were deaf

00:34:05.180 --> 00:34:09.120
were taught the skills
they needed to know.

00:34:09.120 --> 00:34:13.190
So I would take my mainstream
courses with other students,

00:34:13.190 --> 00:34:16.210
and then take an hour
each day to learn Braille,

00:34:16.210 --> 00:34:19.480
learn to use
assistive technology,

00:34:19.480 --> 00:34:24.030
learn to use a cane,
learn to do life skills,

00:34:24.030 --> 00:34:26.880
like cooking non-visually.

00:34:26.880 --> 00:34:29.790
It's all about finding
alternative techniques

00:34:29.790 --> 00:34:36.156
that allow you to succeed,
and pursue your dreams.

00:34:36.156 --> 00:34:38.489
FEMALE SPEAKER: Bethany's
saying, your story about dance

00:34:38.489 --> 00:34:39.510
was wonderful.

00:34:39.510 --> 00:34:42.650
What other types of visual,
or oral information,

00:34:42.650 --> 00:34:47.719
would you like to know about
from the physical world?

00:34:47.719 --> 00:34:52.230
HABEN GIRMA: So usually people
will type visual information

00:34:52.230 --> 00:34:53.850
from the physical world.

00:34:53.850 --> 00:34:58.030
So when someone's typing, they
might use an exclamation mark,

00:34:58.030 --> 00:35:02.370
or type colon,
right parentheses,

00:35:02.370 --> 00:35:07.780
or just type S-M-I-L-E.

00:35:07.780 --> 00:35:11.570
Friends will also describe
what someone is wearing,

00:35:11.570 --> 00:35:15.090
or interesting
artwork on the wall.

00:35:15.090 --> 00:35:17.650
Lots of descriptions.

00:35:17.650 --> 00:35:21.360
There's also something
called Pro-Tactile,

00:35:21.360 --> 00:35:25.290
which transfers some of
that information physically.

00:35:25.290 --> 00:35:31.170
So someone could draw smile
on my arm, or signal laughter.

00:35:31.170 --> 00:35:32.920
There's sign language.

00:35:32.920 --> 00:35:35.030
And I could put my
hand on someone's hand

00:35:35.030 --> 00:35:37.660
and feel what they're signing.

00:35:37.660 --> 00:35:42.480
So there's that whole
world of communicating

00:35:42.480 --> 00:35:47.550
visual information in
an alternative format.

00:35:47.550 --> 00:35:49.860
And I knew that.

00:35:49.860 --> 00:35:54.160
But until two weeks ago,
it never occurred to me

00:35:54.160 --> 00:35:56.630
to do that while dancing.

00:35:56.630 --> 00:36:00.110
So for 10 years, people have
been smiling at me on the dance

00:36:00.110 --> 00:36:01.250
floor, and I didn't know.

00:36:01.250 --> 00:36:03.420
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:03.420 --> 00:36:04.980
But I learned.

00:36:04.980 --> 00:36:08.570
And I'm really grateful to have
that additional information.

00:36:08.570 --> 00:36:11.400
And I'm excited to use it
the next time I go dancing.

00:36:11.400 --> 00:36:13.084
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:13.335 --> 00:36:14.710
FEMALE SPEAKER:
Boston says, it's

00:36:14.710 --> 00:36:17.640
really awesome to see Haben
speak for the first time,

00:36:17.640 --> 00:36:18.500
in person.

00:36:18.500 --> 00:36:19.550
He has two questions.

00:36:19.550 --> 00:36:23.500
The first one is, are there any
suites of apps on your iPhone

00:36:23.500 --> 00:36:27.000
that are tailored for
a blind-deaf person?

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:29.790
And the second is, do you
follow any medical innovations

00:36:29.790 --> 00:36:31.330
that help blind-deaf persons?

00:36:34.320 --> 00:36:38.680
HABEN GIRMA: I feel like I'm
so busy living, and working,

00:36:38.680 --> 00:36:41.530
and dancing, and
talking with friends,

00:36:41.530 --> 00:36:45.950
that I don't have time left
over to follow medical research.

00:36:45.950 --> 00:36:48.870
But I ask friends
and family to let

00:36:48.870 --> 00:36:51.600
me know if they've heard
of something exciting,

00:36:51.600 --> 00:36:53.220
or something new.

00:36:53.220 --> 00:36:55.120
Because I'm open to
new possibilities.

00:36:55.120 --> 00:36:58.470
And I love new research,
and new developments,

00:36:58.470 --> 00:37:01.690
and learning new things.

00:37:01.690 --> 00:37:06.060
I have an app on my
phone called BlindSquare.

00:37:06.060 --> 00:37:09.490
And BlindSquare
is a travel tool.

00:37:09.490 --> 00:37:12.160
And it'll tell you how
to get from point A

00:37:12.160 --> 00:37:16.470
to point B. What's the
nearby intersection?

00:37:16.470 --> 00:37:19.780
What's your approximate address?

00:37:19.780 --> 00:37:24.500
It's designed to be 100%
compatible with a screen reader

00:37:24.500 --> 00:37:26.560
called VoiceOver on the iPhone.

00:37:29.650 --> 00:37:35.910
I would love to have Google Maps
be 100% accessible because that

00:37:35.910 --> 00:37:39.410
has so many features,
and so many potentials.

00:37:39.410 --> 00:37:41.990
But it's not at that level yet.

00:37:41.990 --> 00:37:46.150
So Boston, if you know people
working on Google Maps,

00:37:46.150 --> 00:37:50.330
could you share
this message for me?

00:37:50.330 --> 00:37:54.580
It's actually not that
difficult to make these services

00:37:54.580 --> 00:37:57.000
accessible with screen readers.

00:37:57.000 --> 00:37:59.440
there a guides here at Google.

00:37:59.440 --> 00:38:02.400
So, Google has
accessibility guidelines.

00:38:02.400 --> 00:38:04.210
And there's information
on how to make

00:38:04.210 --> 00:38:06.200
most services accessible.

00:38:06.200 --> 00:38:10.490
I think people maybe
just don't know, and need

00:38:10.490 --> 00:38:15.320
to be reminded, that people
are out there excited to use

00:38:15.320 --> 00:38:20.160
these services, and are
waiting to make them happen.

00:38:20.160 --> 00:38:22.390
Thanks to [? Gopi ?]
for making this happen,

00:38:22.390 --> 00:38:27.042
and, [INAUDIBLE] and
[? Umrit, ?] and Grace.

00:38:27.042 --> 00:38:29.250
FEMALE SPEAKER: Christy was
thanking Haben for coming

00:38:29.250 --> 00:38:31.380
and talking to us today.

00:38:31.380 --> 00:38:34.510
Christy's asking, I have a
family friend who's disabled,

00:38:34.510 --> 00:38:37.670
and studying to be involved
in disability advocacy.

00:38:37.670 --> 00:38:42.914
Do you have any advice
I can pass along to her?

00:38:42.914 --> 00:38:44.580
HABEN GIRMA: It's
really, really helpful

00:38:44.580 --> 00:38:47.010
to connect with the
disability community.

00:38:47.010 --> 00:38:50.070
So when I was thinking
about going into law school,

00:38:50.070 --> 00:38:53.970
I reached out to the blind,
and the deaf community.

00:38:53.970 --> 00:38:56.110
And I talked to a
bunch of deaf lawyers.

00:38:56.110 --> 00:38:58.130
How did you make it
through law school?

00:38:58.130 --> 00:39:00.020
What advice do you have for me?

00:39:00.020 --> 00:39:02.120
And I reached out to
the National Federation

00:39:02.120 --> 00:39:05.560
of the Blind and asked,
all their blind lawyers,

00:39:05.560 --> 00:39:08.940
what advice do you have for
me for going to law school?

00:39:08.940 --> 00:39:10.620
What are the
alternative techniques

00:39:10.620 --> 00:39:13.520
you use for getting your books?

00:39:13.520 --> 00:39:17.380
For doing online research?

00:39:17.380 --> 00:39:20.870
So every disability
experience is very unique.

00:39:20.870 --> 00:39:24.190
So my advice would be connect
with that specific disability

00:39:24.190 --> 00:39:29.130
community, and get advice from
people who have tried that,

00:39:29.130 --> 00:39:34.420
or have done something--
who have done

00:39:34.420 --> 00:39:37.670
something in a related area.

00:39:37.670 --> 00:39:40.020
FEMALE SPEAKER: Sarah's
saying, you've inspired us all.

00:39:40.020 --> 00:39:43.720
You mentioned that Helen Keller
went to Harvard 100 years ago.

00:39:43.720 --> 00:39:45.960
Following your
tremendous success,

00:39:45.960 --> 00:39:49.260
are you seeing more people
that are deaf-blind modeling

00:39:49.260 --> 00:39:50.020
your success?

00:39:50.020 --> 00:39:51.760
Going to Harvard,
and law school?

00:39:54.600 --> 00:39:57.120
HABEN GIRMA: I need to correct
something I said earlier.

00:39:57.120 --> 00:40:02.650
So at the time of Helen
Keller, Harvard, strangely,

00:40:02.650 --> 00:40:05.140
with only men.

00:40:05.140 --> 00:40:10.360
And the equivalent for
women was Radcliffe College.

00:40:10.360 --> 00:40:14.750
Later Harvard opened
its doors to women,

00:40:14.750 --> 00:40:18.760
and Radcliffe College became
part of Harvard University.

00:40:18.760 --> 00:40:22.430
So technically, at the time, it
was called Radcliffe College.

00:40:22.430 --> 00:40:26.140
But it's now part of
Harvard University.

00:40:26.140 --> 00:40:30.070
And more, and more
people with disabilities

00:40:30.070 --> 00:40:36.150
are going to law school,
and are getting educations.

00:40:36.150 --> 00:40:41.650
I don't know of any other
deaf-blind students at Harvard.

00:40:41.650 --> 00:40:44.500
But I do know,
currently, there are

00:40:44.500 --> 00:40:48.870
other blind students, and other
deaf students at Harvard Law

00:40:48.870 --> 00:40:50.270
School.

00:40:50.270 --> 00:40:52.600
And I know of
deaf-blind students

00:40:52.600 --> 00:40:56.750
who are going to other law
schools throughout the country.

00:40:56.750 --> 00:41:00.070
A lot of this is
because the technology,

00:41:00.070 --> 00:41:03.920
and because people like
you are taking the time

00:41:03.920 --> 00:41:07.160
to make sure that services
are accessible to people

00:41:07.160 --> 00:41:09.100
with disabilities.

00:41:09.100 --> 00:41:12.600
I can't imagine trying to have
gone to law school at a time

00:41:12.600 --> 00:41:19.210
without all the services
we now have available.

00:41:19.210 --> 00:41:19.980
So thank you.

00:41:21.780 --> 00:41:24.530
[APPLAUSE]

